st-medieval exrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Bourne","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived beside a stream, from southern Middle English <i>bourne</i>, Old English <i>burna</i>, <i>burne</i> ‘spring, stream’, or a habitational name from a place called with this word, for example Bourn in Cambridgeshire or Bourne in Lincolnshire. In surnames the reference is often to an old stream called <i>burna</i>, surviving as the name of a farm. This word was replaced as the general word for a stream in southern dialects by Old English <i>brōc</i> (see   Brook  ) and came to be restricted in meaning to a stream flowing only intermittently, especially in winter."]},{"name":"Bourns","meanings":["English: variant of   Bournes  . This surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Hervey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which is derived from a Breton personal name composed of <i>haer</i> ‘battle’ + <i>vy</i> ‘worthy’. It was introduced to Britain by Bretons who settled in East Anglia and elsewhere in the wake of the Norman Conquest."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Hervey De Bourges was born about 1046 as the son of Geoffroi de Bourges. He married Judith Malet in 1076, in Great Bealings, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1086, in Clopton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"Abt 1046–1086":"umbes 1046–1086","1046–1086":"1046–1086","1050–1096":"1050–1096","1050–Male":"1050–Surnud","1056–Female":"1056–Surnud","1072–1121":"1072–1121","1075–Male":"1075–Surnud","1018–1061":"1018–1061","1121":"1121","1076":"1076","1086":"1086","1075":"1075","1096":"1096","1061":"1061","1072":"1072","1050":"1050","Abt 1075":"umbes 1075","1018":"1018","Abt 1046":"umbes 1046","1046":"1046","1056":"1056","Abt 1072":"umbes 1072","Great Bealings, Suffolk, England":"Great Be